## Alternatives considered

The main area for alternative considerations is authentication. The following were considered:
<ul><li>Passwords are the most common methods of authentication. However passwords are prone to phishing attacks and bad hygiene that weakens effectiveness. They are described as “low quality” security by the Government Design Service.</li><li>Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) requires two or more independent ways to identify a user. Examples include codes generated from smartphones, captcha tests, fingerprints, voice biometrics, facial recognition and so on. MFA is good against most hacks, but comes with its own pitfalls such as lost phones, SIM cards etc. Orbital analysts will not have access to mobile phones while working so MFA involving smartphones cannot be the default for all user groups. However, orbital analysts will have access to a hardware authentication device. </li><li>While MFA can be explored post-MVP, magic links will be secure and accessible for all user groups and therefore will be the MVP authentication. Problems with magic links expiring before the user can access them will be addressed via longer session times.</li></ul>

## Cross-cutting concerns
The design will conform with the cross-cutting concerns, such as observability, privacy and security, decided and documented elsewhere for MmS.




